  "prompt": "Why do so many people believe that the IQ test determines your intelligence?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why the IQ test has gained widespread credibility, despite its limitations:\n\n1. Historical context\n- Early psychological research presented IQ tests as scientific measurements\n- Perceived objectivity of numerical scoring\n- Academic and professional endorsement\n\n2. Simplicity\n- Single number seems easy to understand\n- Provides a quick, quantifiable assessment\n- Appears to offer a straightforward way to measure cognitive ability\n\n3. Cultural bias\n- Western educational systems have long used standardized testing\n- Belief that cognitive abilities can be numerically ranked\n- Tendency to trust seemingly scientific measurements\n\n4. Partial accuracy\n- IQ tests do measure certain cognitive skills\n- Correlate with academic and professional performance to some extent\n- Can identify some specific cognitive strengths/weaknesses\n\n5. Psychological appeal\n- People like clear, definitive categorizations\n- Desire to understand and quantify personal capabilities\n- Provides a sense of identity or potential\n\nHowever, most modern psychologists recognize that:\n- Intelligence is multifaceted\n- IQ tests have inherent cultural and socioeconomic biases\n- Emotional intelligence, creativity, and practical skills aren't measured\n- Individual potential can't be reduced to a single number\n\nThe belief persists due to a combination of historical momentum and psychological comfort with simple explanations.",
